.R.A. Fisher, J.B.S. Haldane, and Sewall Wright, in pioneering works, confirmed the usefulness of mathematical theory in population genetics. The synthesis their work achieved is recognized today as mathematical genetics, that branch of genetics whose aim is to investigate the laws governing the genetic structure of natural populations and, consequently, to clarify the mechanisms of evolution.For the benefit of population geneticists without advanced mathematical training, Professors Kimura and Ohta use verbal description rather than mathematical symbolism wherever practicable. A mathematical appendix is included.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPopulation geneticsxMathematical models. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Genetics & Genomics.2bisacsh  aF-statistics.  aG-C content.  aK distribution.  aMalthusian parameter.  aOrdovician.  aadaptive surface.  aapparent.  abreeding structure.  achromosomal variation.  adarwin.  aevolutionary rates.  afossils, living.  ainsulins.  alethal equivalent.  alinkage disequilibrium.  amutation, advantageous.  anatural selection.  aquasi-equilibrium surface.  arate of.  aselection.  aselective values.  asteady flux equation.  aviability polygenes.1 aOhta, Tomoko, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691210094423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691210094.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK